People who preorder now will get their robots in spring of 2018.

00:28:13.800 --> 00:28:18.150
So my role as a CTO has changed a lot as the company has grown.

00:28:18.150 --> 00:28:21.835
When we first started and, we were a company of only seven people or so,

00:28:21.835 --> 00:28:24.685
I was lead of all things technical

00:28:24.685 --> 00:28:27.970
and in charge of kind of the general architecture of the robot.

00:28:27.970 --> 00:28:30.190
So, it was a lot of choosing what

00:28:30.190 --> 00:28:33.030
processors do we use and what do we use for the drive chain.

00:28:33.030 --> 00:28:35.230
And what do we use for sensing,

00:28:35.230 --> 00:28:36.520
for mapping and navigation,

00:28:36.520 --> 00:28:37.825
and what algorithms do we use,

00:28:37.825 --> 00:28:40.085
and how do we hide the camera.

00:28:40.085 --> 00:28:41.303
And should we use a camera,

00:28:41.303 --> 00:28:43.480
should we use a screen versus eyes,

00:28:43.480 --> 00:28:45.595
that sort of thing.

00:28:45.595 --> 00:28:48.350
And also I was just part of the software team writing

00:28:48.350 --> 00:28:52.180
actual software for things like mapping and navigation or just robot functions.

00:28:52.180 --> 00:28:54.541
As the team grew,

00:28:54.541 --> 00:28:57.875
we hired a lot of more people to write software and to build robots.

00:28:57.875 --> 00:29:00.790
And so I passed a lot stuff off to those people and then

00:29:00.790 --> 00:29:03.955
I was primarily managing people for a while to build robots.

00:29:03.955 --> 00:29:07.195
And then, finally, we hired managers to manage the people that are building robots.

00:29:07.195 --> 00:29:09.760
And, so, I no longer had to manage all the people.

00:29:09.760 --> 00:29:12.760
So, now, I'm actually back to writing code and I

00:29:12.760 --> 00:29:16.330
lead a small team focused on mapping navigation localization software.

00:29:16.330 --> 00:29:19.645
And that might sound odd as a very narrow thing for a CTO to do.

00:29:19.645 --> 00:29:22.480
But that's actually a very typical CTO transition

00:29:22.480 --> 00:29:25.120
from a small startup to a large company.

00:29:25.120 --> 00:29:26.422
We're over 50 people now.

00:29:26.422 --> 00:29:29.410
So we have a lot of people to build robots and do things.

00:29:29.410 --> 00:29:33.385
And another big part of my role is to get out there and evangelize our tech to the world.

00:29:33.385 --> 00:29:37.750
And let everyone know that Kuri is awesome and full of great technology.

00:29:37.750 --> 00:29:40.630
My proudest thing as CTO is the choice that we

00:29:40.630 --> 00:29:43.750
made for the eyes in deciding that Kuri wasn't going to have a screen,

00:29:43.750 --> 00:29:45.540
Kuri was going to have actual physical eyes.

00:29:45.540 --> 00:29:49.585
And, I think, it makes Kuri look a lot more lifelike and compelling in this way.

00:29:49.585 --> 00:29:53.160
And it also makes us not just another tablet on wheels.

00:29:53.160 --> 00:29:56.655
There's a lot of parents who want to limit screen time for their kids and they say,

00:29:56.655 --> 00:30:00.090
"Oh you can play with this tablet that's fine but only for a little while."

00:30:00.090 --> 00:30:02.200
And, another tablet on wheels,

00:30:02.200 --> 00:30:05.845
maybe is more of the same whereas Kuri is definitely not in that category.

00:30:05.845 --> 00:30:07.230
Kuri is a pet,

00:30:07.230 --> 00:30:08.310
a companion, a friend.

00:30:08.310 --> 00:30:12.680
For me, my favorite part is actually working on the robot's algorithms.

00:30:12.680 --> 00:30:14.610
Things like mapping and navigation that I get

00:30:14.610 --> 00:30:16.255
to focus on these days which is a lot of fun.

00:30:16.255 --> 00:30:18.120
And the sensors involved in designing

00:30:18.120 --> 00:30:20.980
the sensors and making sure all that sort of thing works well.

00:30:20.980 --> 00:30:24.690
I mean, I'm a roboticist at heart and that's the,

00:30:24.690 --> 00:30:26.270
really, the most fun part for me.

00:30:26.270 --> 00:30:28.020
One of the things I was most surprised at,

00:30:28.020 --> 00:30:32.415
was just how many people have the robot dream of, "I really want a robot.

00:30:32.415 --> 00:30:34.610
My own R2-D2 version et cetera"

00:30:34.610 --> 00:30:37.095
And I thought that was kind of limited to,

00:30:37.095 --> 00:30:38.670
you know, geeks and engineers or something.

00:30:38.670 --> 00:30:40.050
And, it turns out, that's pretty widespread.

00:30:40.050 --> 00:30:42.185
There's a lot of people out there who really have that dream.

00:30:42.185 --> 00:30:44.160
Other random things that we found through testing

00:30:44.160 --> 00:30:47.055
that was really surprising to me are things like,

00:30:47.055 --> 00:30:51.261
a lot of people don't understand top down maps.

00:30:51.261 --> 00:30:54.390
So, as a roboticists we're used to seeing, for instance,

00:30:54.390 --> 00:30:56.280
navigation maps from the robot and then

00:30:56.280 --> 00:30:58.905
specifying where you want the robot to go by saying,

00:30:58.905 --> 00:31:01.177
"In the map I would like you to go over here".

00:31:01.177 --> 00:31:03.990
And when we first started,

00:31:03.990 --> 00:31:05.670
one of the very first test we did

00:31:05.670 --> 00:31:07.965
was with a functional prototype that looked nothing like Kuri.

00:31:07.965 --> 00:31:10.530
And just with an app and we had an interface where you

00:31:10.530 --> 00:31:13.645
could tell the robot to go various places using a top down map.

00:31:13.645 --> 00:31:16.110
And, most people could not understand the map,

00:31:16.110 --> 00:31:18.360
and could not understand where the robot was,

00:31:18.360 --> 00:31:19.865
and where they were telling him to go.

00:31:19.865 --> 00:31:21.435
And, not even just,

00:31:21.435 --> 00:31:23.445
we're used to laser maps being somewhat difficult.

00:31:23.445 --> 00:31:25.188
Because, you know, it's only black and white,

00:31:25.188 --> 00:31:27.930
it's from the level of the laser it's a 2-D map.

00:31:27.930 --> 00:31:31.455
It doesn't necessarily resemble what you think of as a floor plan for your home.

00:31:31.455 --> 00:31:34.200
Like you might see, like, on the wall - the emergency floor plan,

00:31:34.200 --> 00:31:37.090
this is where the exit is, et cetera.

00:31:37.090 --> 00:31:39.680
But even the emergency exit plans,

00:31:39.680 --> 00:31:41.210
a lot people can't understand those.

00:31:41.210 --> 00:31:45.230
And we actually took a top down color maps of

00:31:45.230 --> 00:31:47.480
the room which Kuri could not ever actually

00:31:47.480 --> 00:31:50.030
get because Kuri can't see above table height for instance.

00:31:50.030 --> 00:31:54.185
But, we took scanners that were able to scan the room from a much higher height

00:31:54.185 --> 00:31:56.270
and could make full color renders

00:31:56.270 --> 00:31:59.180
of this is what your entire room looks like from the top down.

00:31:59.180 --> 00:32:01.065
And can people even use that interface?

00:32:01.065 --> 00:32:03.425
And the answer was, no. Most people can't.

00:32:03.425 --> 00:32:05.525
And, so, we had to upend the idea of

00:32:05.525 --> 00:32:08.900
specifying navigation waypoints by top down map entirely,

00:32:08.900 --> 00:32:12.340
so that users who can't understand them can still use the robot.

00:32:12.340 --> 00:32:14.325
So we moved instead towards,

00:32:14.325 --> 00:32:16.175
you drive the robot to a place,

00:32:16.175 --> 00:32:18.605
and you see what the robot is seeing through his camera,

00:32:18.605 --> 00:32:21.560
and you can save that point as a location in your house,

00:32:21.560 --> 00:32:23.889
and both has a name and has a picture.

00:32:23.889 --> 00:32:25.205
And that's very intuitive to people,

00:32:25.205 --> 00:32:27.815
if you just click on that then you know where you're sending the robot.

00:32:27.815 --> 00:32:30.400
And he will go back to where you put him in the first place.

00:32:30.400 --> 00:32:32.000
Another very surprising thing to me,

00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:34.920
in terms of user interfaces, was joysticking.

00:32:34.920 --> 00:32:40.025
A lot of people can't actually joystick the robot with a basic joystick interface that,

00:32:40.025 --> 00:32:42.410
you you press forward and the robot moves forward.

00:32:42.410 --> 00:32:45.990
When they're looking at the robot and they press forward the robot,

00:32:45.990 --> 00:32:47.820
they think it's forward from their point of view.

00:32:47.820 --> 00:32:49.370
They don't necessarily understand

00:32:49.370 --> 00:32:52.040
the transformation of forward from the robot's point of view.

00:32:52.040 --> 00:32:55.385
And some people never get that even after a lot of practice.

00:32:55.385 --> 00:32:58.250
And, so, we're still working now on exactly

00:32:58.250 --> 00:33:01.600
like what best interfaces to give people to allow them to move around.

00:33:01.600 --> 00:33:04.970
But some things that we've tried that people seem to enjoy are things like,

00:33:04.970 --> 00:33:07.280
you can click in the image to make the robot drive there.

00:33:07.280 --> 00:33:08.570
And that's intuitive because you're

00:33:08.570 --> 00:33:10.250
looking at an image and you know where you're clicking on.

00:33:10.250 --> 00:33:14.095
In the image you know where the robot's going to go. That's much more intuitive.

00:33:14.095 --> 00:33:18.230
In developing Kuri, I guess I've learned more about people than about robots even.

00:33:18.230 --> 00:33:19.685
I mean I have learned a lot about robots.

00:33:19.685 --> 00:33:21.575
Making robots is insanely complicated.

00:33:21.575 --> 00:33:24.060
And I like to say the devil's in the details.

00:33:24.060 --> 00:33:27.305
If you get any little detail wrong that could be the thing that sinks your robot.

00:33:27.305 --> 00:33:30.580
It's just useless if any one of those things is very wrong.

00:33:30.580 --> 00:33:34.865
But making Kuri successful is all about human-robot interaction,

00:33:34.865 --> 00:33:39.095
and about design, and about making things intuitive and compelling and lifelike.

00:33:39.095 --> 00:33:42.830
And a lot of that has to do more about how people actually are,

00:33:42.830 --> 00:33:44.030
or how people react to things,

00:33:44.030 --> 00:33:45.580
or what people can understand.

00:33:45.580 --> 00:33:49.720
And, a lot of that goes into making the robot successful.

00:33:49.720 --> 00:33:51.530
The key to success for a home robot, I think,

00:33:51.530 --> 00:33:57.700
is in personality and in getting the robot to look lifelike and accepted in the home.

00:33:57.700 --> 00:34:00.690
And a lot of that has to do with getting the interaction right with

00:34:00.690 --> 00:34:03.915
the people and getting the look of the robot's right so he looks lifelike.

00:34:03.915 --> 00:34:06.020
And so that he's accepted in the home

00:34:06.020 --> 00:34:09.860
as a member of your family something that you see everyday trundling around.

00:34:09.860 --> 00:34:12.310
He has to be compelling. He has to be adorable.

00:34:12.310 --> 00:34:14.210
So my advice to you is,

00:34:14.210 --> 00:34:15.710
robotics is a great field.

00:34:15.710 --> 00:34:17.285
There are a lot of fun jobs in robots,

00:34:17.285 --> 00:34:19.905
especially today roboticists are highly sought after.

00:34:19.905 --> 00:34:21.905
I know because I'm trying to hire and it's really hard.

00:34:21.905 --> 00:34:23.675
And there are a lot,

00:34:23.675 --> 00:34:26.625
you should go out there and build lots of robots and have lots of fun.

00:34:26.625 --> 00:34:29.630
One thing I'm looking for a lot in a roboticist right now is,

00:34:29.630 --> 00:34:33.190
we're looking for software engineers and so we want very strong programming skills.

00:34:33.190 --> 00:34:36.338
And so a lot of roboticist coming out of school,

00:34:36.338 --> 00:34:39.980
they know how to program robots but they don't know much about software carpentry.

00:34:39.980 --> 00:34:42.200
So learning the basics of how to write tests,

00:34:42.200 --> 00:34:43.805
and how to do continuous integration,

00:34:43.805 --> 00:34:47.990
and having really good skills in writing things like C++ and Python.

00:34:47.990 --> 00:34:49.570
Those are all very important to us.

00:34:49.570 --> 00:34:53.995
So one of the biggest things I've learned about trying to start this company.

00:34:53.995 --> 00:34:55.265
I thought when we started this company,

00:34:55.265 --> 00:34:57.760
"Oh this is my chance to learn all the ins and outs on

00:34:57.760 --> 00:35:00.450
how to make adorable consumer robots, awesome consumer robots."

00:35:00.450 --> 00:35:02.270
And, what I've learned is the way you make

00:35:02.270 --> 00:35:05.630
